observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Management should:
Instruct the Inventory Committee to properly plan and conduct a regular physical count of PPE in lieu of the one-time cleansing in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020;
Enjoin the Inventory Committee to submit to this office the required correct format of RPCPPE on or before January 31 of the ensuing year;
Schedule and complete the reconciliation of the results of inventory count to ensure that all PPEs counted are duly recorded in the respective records of Property and Accounting Units; and
Require the Property and Accounting Units to maintain and update the PPE stock cards and PPE ledger cards, respectively.

We recommended that the Management should:
Instruct the Motor pool Officer, to assess the condition of this heavy equipment with due consideration of the 30% allowable limit of repairs to avoid excessive expenditures set in COA Circular No. 2012-003 dated October 29, 2012;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to conduct cost-benefit analysis and consider disposal pursuant to COA-DBM Joint Circular 2024-1 dated January 30, 2024 if it is beyond economic repair to avoid unnecessary expenditures under COA Circular No. 2012-003 dated October 29, 2012;
Instruct the GSO to regularly monitor the condition of all heavy equipment/motor vehicles of the Municipality, including repairs and maintenance thereof and establish them in the records thru proper documentation; and
Henceforth, exercise due diligence of a good father of a family in dealing with property management and utilization thereof to avoid wastage of government resources in the future.

a. Identify the relevant road asset components first and separate them from the entire road asset so that these shall not be provided with the residual value;

b. Compute the correct depreciation expense in accordance with COA Circular No. 2015-008 dated November 23, 2015; and

c. Submit Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) for the adjusting entry to correct the balances of the affected accounts.

a. Instruct the MBO to set-up or allocate necessary funds for terminal leave benefits by accruing the actual earned leave benefits of all officials and employees of the Municipality, including those of the members of the Sangguniang Bayan;

b. Enjoin the Municipal Accountant to take up as one of the adjusting entries at year-end the accrued liability, and include a disclosure in the Notes to Financial Statement the details of such amount; and

Henceforth, ensure that all disbursement of terminal leave benefits must be supported with complete documentary requirements as required by COA Circular No. 2012-001.

Exert effort in the processing of Certificate of Title of the untitled lots in order to establish absolute ownership and protect legal interest pursuant to Section 148 of COA Circular 92-386;

b. Allocate fund intended for the survey/relocation, titling of these lots and appraisal of the structures built on the properties; and

Direct the Municipal Assessors Office to facilitate and supervise the proper proceedings for the land titling and immediate transfer to the Municipality to ascertain the ownership.

The Committee also shall include in the RPCPPE the name of the person to whom the property was assigned.  The General Services Office (GSO) or its equivalent shall update the Acknowledgment Receipt of Equipment (ARE) to have a current record of the property and the accountable person in charge of the property. This report must be duly accomplished before submitted to the Office of the Mayor and before distribution of copies to the Municipal Offices and the Auditor.

Review COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 on the procedural guidelines on the conduct of one-time cleansing;

Instruct the Inventory Committee to properly plan, conduct and prioritize the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances in accordance with the above-cited regulation;

Conduct the disposal of unserviceable properties;

Schedule the reconciliation of the results of inventory count to ensure that all PPEs included in the RPCPPE are duly recorded in the respective records of the Property and Accounting Units;

Require the Property and Accounting Units to maintain and update the PPE stock cards and PPE ledger cards, respectively; 

Require the Property and Accounting Units to update the RPCPPE and lapsing schedule as to details and description.

Enjoin the Inventory Committee to plan and schedule the conduct of annual physical count of PPE to ensure that the required RPCPPE as December 31 of the succeeding years is prepared and submitted to this office on or before January 31 of the ensuing year.

Recommendation
We recommended and management agreed to undertake the following:
Instruct the Inventory Committee to properly plan and conduct a regular physical count of PPE in line with the one-time cleansing in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020;
Enjoin the Inventory Committee to submit to this office the required RPCPPE on or before January 31 of the ensuing year;
Schedule and complete the reconciliation of the results of inventory count to ensure that all PPEs counted are duly recorded in the respective records of Property and Accounting Units; and
Require the Property and Accounting Units to maintain and update the PPE stock cards and PPE ledger cards, respectively.

We have recommended to the management to:

Direct the Municipal Treasurer to prepare a duly certified list of taxpayers with corresponding amount of tax due and collectible for the year which should be the basis of the Municipal Accountant in setting up RPT/SET Receivable at the beginning of the year;

Require the Municipal Assessor to update information of taxpayers and of properties that will affect the assessment roll and to prepare a reconciliation statement showing the items that caused the differences of the RPT/SET Collectibles found in the QRRPA and the assessment rolls to determine which items can be resolved by the LGU;

Enjoin the Municipal Accountant to prepare journal entries to adjust the RPT/SET receivables account to reflect their true balances in the LGU’s books and to set up these receivables at the beginning of the year in accordance with Section 20, Chapter 3, Volume I of the Manual on New Government Accounting System (MNGAS) for LGU

